<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
KAREEM TAKES ON FILM PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Less than a year after retiring from basketball, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar has 
bounced back into the public eye with an executive producer berth on the motion 
picture "Recruiting Violations." 
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Jabbar was tapped for the project on the basis of his basketball 
expertise. 
</P>
<P>
The movie centers on the relationship between a white college basketball coach 
and a top black recruit who fails to show up on campus. 
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Jabbar will be involved in development of the screenplay and packaging of 
the film, said Rob Fried, whose Fried Films is making the movie for Columbia 
Pictures. 
</P>
<P>
The former Los Angeles Lakers star won't be appearing in the film. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't foresee that. I just want to do this on the production end and get my 
feet wet that way," Abdul-Jabbar said. 
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Jabbar is currently touring with his book "Kareem," and he expresses 
mixed feelings on the possibility of a motion picture version of the book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
