NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
MIKE WALLACE TO TURN ZESTFUL 72 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mike Wallace, veteran correspondent for CBS' "60 Minutes," turns 72 on May 9 
but says, "I've got the zest, the energy I've always had." 
</P>
<P>
And age can help, he told TV Guide in its April 21 issue. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm old enough and experienced enough so that people are more willing to talk 
more openly to me than they used to be," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"There's been a strange difference in the last few years in the manner an 
interview with me is perceived. I'm considered less of a threat." 
</P>
<P>
He said he can feel sorry for colleagues trying to start a television news 
magazine: "When I started with '60 Minutes' in 1968, no one was watching. That 
took away a lot of pressure." 
</P>
</TEXT>
